  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming the Double Coat, and Why We Don't Shave It" imageAlt="Pomeranian puppy being brushed through its double coat" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The coat is the Pomeranian's crown and its chore. Plan on brushing 3 to 4 times a week down to the skin, not just over the top, plus a proper groom every 4 to 8 weeks. Shedding is constant and the seasonal coat blows are generous; the vacuum becomes part of the family.</p>
      <p>One thing we tell every buyer, because Singapore groomers see the damage weekly: don't shave a Pomeranian down for the "teddy bear cut". Shaving a double coat can trigger alopecia X, patchy hair loss that may never fully grow back. Trim, tidy, and brush; never shave to the skin. In our climate the undercoat actually insulates against heat, so a well-brushed full coat is more comfortable than a shaved one.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Pomeranian Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Pomeranian puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Pomeranian goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Pomeranian health points worth knowing: patellar luxation, the kneecap issue common to toy breeds; tracheal collapse, a weakness of the windpipe in tiny dogs, which is why your starter-kit harness is not optional and collars should never take leash pressure; dental crowding, so the oral care routine starts on day one; and alopecia X, the coat-loss condition linked to shaving, which the grooming advice above avoids.</p>
      <p>Very young Pomeranian puppies can also run low blood sugar, which regular small meals prevent; your puppy comes home with the food it is already eating and a feeding routine to follow. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Truth About Teacup Pomeranians" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>The Pomeranian is one of the top targets of "teacup" marketing in Singapore, because at a healthy 1.5 to 3.5 kg it is already tiny. You will see "teacup pom" listings, often at a premium. We don't sell to that label. Dogs bred to be unusually tiny carry higher risks: fragile bones, collapsing tracheas, severe dental problems, chronic low blood sugar, and shorter lives.</p>
      <p>A healthy Pomeranian already fits in a tote bag with room for your wallet. If a seller promises a size below the healthy range and guarantees it, treat the promise as a warning, not a feature.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Teacup red flags</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Guaranteed adult weight below 1.5 kg',
            'No mention of the parents\' actual size',
            '"Teacup" or "micro" priced at a premium',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M18 6 6 18M6 6l12 12" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Pomeranian's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Pomeranian puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Pomeranian explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable. A fixed feeding routine with regular small meals, the toilet pads where we placed them, and short, gentle play. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and the personality arrives. This is the window to book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer, the single best investment against future yappiness; see <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

